Civil rights group warns against travel to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has warned black people traveling to Missouri against state-discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The NAACP travel note issued for the state of Missour, which is valid until August 28, 2017, invites all African-American travelers, visitors and Missourians to be particularly attentive and extremely careful when moving around the state, given the entire series of suspicious race-based events that have recently taken place across the state and have been highlighted here."
According to the NAACP, the group was urged to issue a travel warning, both by the recent Missouri law, which makes it more difficult to win cases of discrimination, and the fact that the targets of state law enforcement are unequally largely minorities.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They're being pulled to the side of the road because of their skin color, they're being beaten or killed," Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri branch of NAACP, told The Kansas City Star.
“We’ve never been so complaints before.”
This is the first such warning issued by the organization about the U.S. state.
The group cited events such as racist insults towards black students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gasoline while driving through the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with the crime.
In addition, the note refers to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General, which shows that in the state, black drivers' cars are 75% more likely to be stopped than those of white people.
“The note is designed to make people aware and warn their families, friends, and co-workers about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared, whether it's taking bail money or informing relatives that they're going through the state."
Based on the latest data from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, Missouri documented 100 hate crimes in 2015, placing the state in 16th place in the state's cross-section in terms of the number of similar violations.
The travel warning is also in response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder for the company to sue for discrimination in search of housing or work.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel remarks about Texas and Arizona after these states passed immigration laws that required local authorities to arrest people for immigration violations because, according to ACLU, it increases racial profiling.
Typically, travel warnings are issued by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs for other countries, but recently, interest groups have started to use this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
Hepatitis: what could everyone know about the different forms of this serious disease?
Hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver, can be caused by five different hepatitis viruses - A, B, C, D and E.
All these viruses provoke acute inflammation of the liver tissue.
However, chronic hepatitis B and C have a malignant course, which can develop into liver cirrhosis, i.e. liver wrinkle and liver cancer.
Kuulo Kutsar, Epidemiology Advisor at the Health Board, says that the symptoms of acute hepatitis are the same for all types of liver inflammation - fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, grayish stools, dark urine, muscle and joint pain, and yellowing of the skin and mucous membranes.
The latter sign of the disease also comes from the popular name for liver inflammation jaundice.
In children, hepatitis may not be known.
Different types of liver inflammation can only be determined on the basis of laboratory test data.
Acute hepatitis can transition to chronic hepatitis and progress for decades without symptoms, which means that a person may not know anything about their dangerous liver-damaging disease.
Kuulo Kutsar highlights different forms of hepatitis and describes their course in more detail.
Hepatitis A viruses spread from a sick person and infect us by eating contaminated food or drinking water, by sex, from the feces of an infected person to hands and hands to food, surfaces, objects, getting into the mouth, and when using drugs.
The risk of contracting hepatitis A, or the risk group, includes family members and caregivers of the infected person, people suffering from chronic liver disease, people having sex with an infected person, men having sex with men, drug addicts, travellers visiting countries with a high incidence of hepatitis A.
Infection can be prevented by vaccination, in particular vaccination is recommended for people who travel heavily and are at risk of hepatitis A.
In addition, it is important to meet the daily hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect your hands, wash all fruits and vegetables before consuming food.
Hepatitis B viruses are spread by contact with the blood of a sick person, by injecting, tattooing, piercing, using household items contaminated with blood (toothbrushes, shaving equipment), donor blood, having sex with a person who is suspected of hepatitis, and from a hepatitis patient to a foetus/neonate.
The risk group for hepatitis B infection includes injecting drug addicts, sex partners of an infected person, men having sex with men, newborns of an infected mother, sick family members and caregivers, health care workers and police officers who are exposed to blood and other body fluids, and travellers visiting countries with high levels of hepatitis B.
It is possible to vaccinate people for the prevention of hepatitis B; in particular, it is recommended to vaccinate people at risk, as well as people with chronic liver diseases, HIV-infected, sexually transmitted diseases and people with diabetes.
Other preventive measures for hepatitis B include: refraining from the use of foreign hygiene and manicure equipment, other sharps and syringe-needles, tattooing and piercing, and the use of a condom in case of dangerous sex or avoidance of sexual risk behavior.
Vaccination against hepatitis B is part of the national immunisation schedule in Estonia and free of charge for children.
Hepatitis C viruses are spread by contact with the blood of a sick person, by injecting, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated household items, donor blood, having sex with a person who is suspicious of hepatitis, and from a mother with hepatitis to a foetus/neonate.
The risk group for hepatitis C infection includes injecting drug users, sex partners of an infected person, men having sex with men, newborns of an infected mother, family members and caregivers of the sick, health care workers and police officers who are exposed to blood and other body fluids, persons infected with HIV, and travellers visiting countries with high levels of hepatitis C.
The preventive measure against hepatitis C is: refraining from the use of foreign hygiene and manicure equipment, other sharps and syringe-needles, tattooing and piercing, and the use of a condom in case of infectious sex.
There is no vaccine for hepatitis C.
Hepatitis D is caused by the hepatitis D virus, which multiplies in the presence of the hepatitis B virus.
Therefore, hepatitis D infection occurs with hepatitis B or as a superinfection in patients with chronic hepatitis B.
Hepatitis D viruses are spread by contact with blood and other body fluids, syringes and needles contaminated with them, sexually and rarely from an infected mother to the fetus.
The risk group for hepatitis D is chronic carriers of hepatitis B virus and people who do not have immunity to hepatitis B.
An effective preventive measure is vaccination with the hepatitis B vaccine, which also protects a person from infection with the hepatitis D virus.
Hepatitis E viruses are spread by faecal-oral drinking water and food, including low-cooked beef, fish and clams, donor blood, shared syringes and from the infected mother to the foetus.
Passengers can become infected with hepatitis E in countries with high levels of disease.
Preventive measures for hepatitis E are compliance with hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect hands after going to the toilet, before cooking and eating, after caring for the sick.
Wash fruits and vegetables before consumption, avoid eating low-cooked beef, fish and seafood, drink only safe drinking water and refrain from drug use.
