Blocking critics from Facebook - Don't run for public office if you can't stand criticism from voters
The father of our country knew a lot about the unfavorable media coverage.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it didn't take long for the newspapers to beat him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
The criticism, of course, upset him.
But he didn't force his critics to remain silent.
Because in 1783, Washington said that "free speech can be taken away from us, and in mute and silent, we can be led to a massacre like a sheep."
It brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who has to work hard to be more like Washington.
Hogani's subordinates have blocked and deleted posts by at least 450 people who published their opinion on their official Facebook page.
And towards the beginning of the week, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) sued him for this.
The governor's officials labeled the action null and void, and online comments were full of counter-reactions in the style of "Who cares?".
“It’s just Facebook,” many said.
But it does count.
And it matters a lot when it comes to a man like Hogan.
He is an amazingly popular Republican governor in an overwhelmingly democratic state.
His approval rate ranks second among the country's 50 governors.
Hogan is not a thoughtlessly responsive windhead.
He has led the state with a firm hand and remained strictly true to his principles.
In addition, he has used Facebook quite as a key tool in communicating with his constituents, for example, by vigorously presenting his bald head for the first time after chemotherapy.
Thus, the governor's page ‖ is a public forum officially marked, managed by staff who receive a salary from taxpayers' dollars  blocking people visiting is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's behavior in an interview with The Washington Post, claiming that blocking the comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it's too easy to paint a picture of online trolls, spammers or people full of anger.
The Post was talking to several real people that Hogan was blocking.
And that's what they are, real people who communicate with their chosen leaders. Teacher, business owner and pastor, not internet trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not at all obscene.
In his post, the pastor quoted the Bible, oppressing Hogan's Catholicism.
Lawyer from Bowie, Maryland, Lakshmi Sarma Ramani, did not incite anger, but on real hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed because he has not responded to hate crimes or other recent news," he wrote in a comment section on The Post's news story.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people comment on the same topic, some immediately call it an indifferent collective effort, instead of admitting that they are a large number of worried citizens."
What the governor's official called "directed spam attack" would probably be called "public support" by others.
The Facebook era allows you to easily match messages by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It's much cleaner than it used to be when, in order to do the same, it was necessary to send out workers so that they would collect newspapers with critical editorials and burn them or arrest the protesters and force them to remain silent.
But that's exactly what's happening right now, just digitally.
Hogan is not the first government official to be criticized for getting Facebook and other social media channels toothless.
President Trump has sued Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first landmark verdicts on this subject was made last week in Virginia.
U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris ruled in Alexandria that the Loudoun County Council of Supervisors ruled out the first amendment of the constitution when he blocked the voter from his Facebook page.
In Kentucky, ACLU also visited Governor Matt Bevin (R) for using Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be so hard.
In Washington time, affordable postage had a similar effect as the internet.
Between 1776 and 1800 quadrupled, the number of newspapers and anonymous writers beat him up for his management.
And even then, Washington had to deal with anonymous trolls.
People wrote letters to newspapers under such pseudonyms as Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius, making Washington's decisions to the ground.
According to historical documents collected in the context of the online George Washington mail collection project, he was buried in the cabinet under petitions criticizing his views on the friendship, trade and shipping agreements with Britain.
But he didn't force them to keep quiet.
Freedom of expression, differences of opinion and debate are the foundations of our country.
And proper management means accepting it.
