"No one dares to go to the village after five o'clock in the evening," he says.
It is a rare glimpse into life in the Papua Highlands. It is a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a controversy referendum, during which only 1026 elderly people were forced to vote by raising their hands in front of the occupant's forces.
The movement that prompted the Dutch's doomsliftment quickly directed its rage against the Jakarta government, which is still keeping the region under its strong control, keeping away foreign journalists and human rights supervisors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, so that the independent Papua New Guinea remained in the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is both a distant and an abandoned place. To get here, you need to fly from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire for 90 minutes, and then take a nauseous five-hour journey on a car.
There is no public transport.
The city, which has a population of about 19 000, consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and covered with wavy iron roofs, the rust of which has turned different shades of yellow-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made the journey here, not to mention journalists, and there have been hardly any foreigners here.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuas of Mee Pago worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
"We weren't used to wearing clothes like this," says Degei, referring to his colorful hand-woven turban, dark blouse and bright skirt.
"Before that, we only carried plant leaves on the body."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of people living below the poverty line and statistics on infant mortality and illiteracy is one of the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's gold-filled land.
Just 100 km from the Pania, a mountainous province of about New Jersey with a population of 153,000, is home to the world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, which is owned by Phoenix-based company Freeport McMoran.
In 2015, Freeport extracted about 3.1 billion USD of gold and copper from here alone.
In addition, Papua can boast of consumer wood stocks estimated at US$78 billion.
But these riches are the source of the Papuan suffering, because they require a powerful suffocating presence of the Indonesian army.
A 2005 study by The New York Times found that Freeport paid approximately US$20 million to local military and military units from 1998 to 2004, including up to US$150,000 to a single officer.
Papuate's efforts to ensure greater autonomy threaten this golden goose and are ruthlessly handled.
Human rights activists say more than 500 000 papuas have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by Indonesia's military.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the Papua tribal highlands were subjected to mass killings in the 1970s to the size of a genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3900 peaceful protesters in the area.
The 2016 report of the Birsbane Archdiocese "We will lose everything" contains testimony about the atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial killings, torture (according to another report, rape and electric shocks are especially common) and brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because such incidents occur every week," says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia's researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screws are even more tightly turned off because Papua's natural resources have caused the influx of new settlers from elsewhere in Indonesia.
83% of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants are Christians, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Kalimantani, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan family canteens sell gado-gado with crispy chicken and mixed vegetables, which is served with peanut sauce.
The locals can't compete with them.
"Migrants began selling chicken and vegetables in the traditional market cheaper than local papuas," explains 24-year-old Abeth You, who was born in Paniai, who moved to the provincial capital, Jayapura, for work.
"The indigenous papuas  papua mama-mama [women]  will therefore lose their market share."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokow, pledged in his 2014 election campaign to address their inequality and human rights violations in Papua.
The former carpenter won 27 of the 29 constituencies in Papua, including Paniai, on his way to the presidential pallet of Jakarta.
But very little has changed in Papua and the locals feel deceived.
"Our hearts have been broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokow in the expectation that he would fulfill our hopes of restoring justice," You says.
In fact, Paniai was in a slump just two months after Jokow took office in October.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children sang Christmas songs by the Enarotalis fire when two Indonesian soldiers appeared on a motorcycle from the dark.
The horrified children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone of voice and later returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and eyewitnesses, drunk soldiers chased the children and beat them with their rifle handles.
Then one of the soldiers shot into the children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so cruelly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby electoral commission building was set on fire, and the next day things escalated further.
About 1000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They wore ceremonial hunting bows and performed a waita dance from the Papuan honey pago tribe, during which they ran around and imitated birdsong.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police and military.
In the event of an outcrop, soldiers were sent orders via internal radio. "If the crowds resist more than three times, shoot them," the official document said, which has been seen by TIME magazine, but which has not been issued to local media outlets.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the elder of the Kego Koto district in the city of Enarotal, felt an impending threat and called for peace to be kept, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist," he told TIME magazine on the porch of his wooden house in bright colors.
Kayame still doesn't know who the shooter was, but he says the bullet came from the assembled soldiers.
"There was a lot of people, there was a lot of shots," he adds.
Alfius Youw, a local man, said his cousin had witnessed the shooting three times.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Yohanes told TIME magazine, using only one name like many Indonesians.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
Papua Police Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his subordinates only ensured the safety of his precinct because it was attacked.
"We must defend ourselves if we are threatened with death," said Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, a spokesman for Papua police in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and heavily injured.
News of the killings didn't arrive in Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a passionate speech in Jayapura, where he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and promised to engage in abuses in Papua.
"I want to resolve this case right away so that it never happens again in the future," he said.
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he would establish an out-of-court mechanism to solve crimes against human rights.
But almost immediately, excuses followed.
"Most of the crimes happened a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the 1990s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to solving these crimes, but we must follow certain processes," he said.
Speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, Wiranto withdrew his words, saying he had no intention of creating a mechanism in Papua to deal with complaints.
Instead, he said, "everything is resolved by law."
Wiranto, accused by the United Nations of human rights crimes over the deaths of more than 1,000 people in East Timor during the 1999 bloody independence referendum, said 11 crimes against human rights have already been solved in Papua, including what happened in Paniai.
The families of the victims of Paniai accepted such claims with gloomy distrust.
"I have been questioned four times in the last three years, but no progress has been made," Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
He says he's still living in fear years later.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid the military will arrest me, I'm afraid I'm going to be shot."
His brother Yacobus said Paniai was afraid to dissect the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury the four victims.
"After burying the bodies, the army came to find me," he says.
The shootings haven't stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in the neighbouring Paniai regenty in Deiyai.
One person was killed and 17 wounded, including children, when he went into an altercation between the villagers and the construction company manager, who refused to transport the unconscious man to the hospital.
This man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned in a nearby river while fishing, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested on the construction site in front of the company's office.
Police said the villagers threw stones at the police, at which point the latter responded with warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian military police) started shooting at the crowd, killing one person.
"We were in a big panic, we're afraid of revenge," said 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the injured people's entries.
"I've been hiding in my house for two days."
Deiyai's parliament has called for the prosecution of the police officers involved and the withdrawal of the police's mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development feeds the dissatisfaction of the honey, moni, dani and damal tribes living in the green central highlands of Papua.
Many of them have joined the Free Papua Movement (VPL), an army of rebels that defend the rights of the Papuans, arbitrarily carrying out attacks and kidnappings among Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the leaders of the VPL are from the Panyah, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, the military, under the pretext of "protecting the sovereignty of the state", has arrested the Paniais in recent years and arbitrarily detained thousands of people.
Some of them will never show up again.
Among the people of Papua, Pania is known as the "tragic forgotten place".
Poverty feeds dissatisfaction.
The little rice that is sold in Enarotal is too expensive to buy for locals.
The bread is just as inaccessible.
People grow all their food themselves �� mainly sweet potatoes, plus a little fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women, each of whom can maintain four or five sweet potato fields.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, the rest are sold in the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10 000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality between indigenous papuas and new migrants, which has arrived since the opening of new routes to Nabire airport, has deepened.
The few jobs that exist go better to educated and wealthier migrants.
Papua themselves often lack capital or the necessary skills to conduct a competitive business.
"Young people are not interested in staying in the village because there are no jobs or money here," says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
The separation keeps the eyes of the world away from Papua.
In addition, strict restrictions on foreign media remain.
Towards the beginning of this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were expelled from Papua because "they did not follow relevant practices" although they had been given a rare filming license.
According to Phelim Kine, Deputy Head of the Asia Department of Human Rights Watch, Jokow's election promises to remove restrictions on reports to promote transparency and development have not been implemented.
"In Indonesia, journalists trying to report on the easternmost troubled provinces of Papua and West Papua are threatened with new threats of visa rejection and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of a drilling gaze in the press means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to Papua's close neighbours.
In March, the Six Pacific states ‖ Tonga, Nauru, Belau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands spurred the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "a variety of widespread crimes" in Papua, including the shooting of Paniai.
The same countries have historically supported the VPL.
Indonesian foreign ministry spokeswoman Arrmanatha Nasir rejected the group's accusations, Jakartas told reporters: "In Indonesia, democratic order and press freedom still apply, so it would be difficult to bury evidence of anti-human rights cases."
Local people want more foreign governments to be noticed.
When the Dutch official delegation, led by the country's human rights ambassador Kees Van Bar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local people interrupted their silence, according to a source who was at the meeting but wished to remain anonymous, asking for "we want freedom."
Indonesia will hold new presidential elections in 2019, but the Papuas do not believe they will vote for Jokow again.
"Jokowi is a man of good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the shooting of Paniai," says Hobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants to imply to Jokow that, in addition to the fact that the people of Paniai are constantly living under the threat of a threat from a predatory army, they are struggling with misery because of poor educational and health services.
According to Gobai, the people of Pania, like other papuas, consider the vote given to their Jokow to be the debt he has to pay.
"They don't need money, they want justice," he says.
Despite the threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the shooting of Paniai managed to withstand the last symbolic insurrection -- they buried the body of one of the victims in the land opposite the police station and the military base.
Knowing that justice may never be established, they at least prevent those responsible from forgetting their crimes.
"One of our family members was killed," says Yacobus with a lowered head.
"What else can we do?"
