EPA overturns decision to postpone smog regulation after actions
The United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has overturned a decision to delay the imposition of an Obama-era order requiring states to limit smog-inducing exhaust gases, one day after 15 states sued the agency for this move.
The EPA announced its decision to continue with the "2015 ozone determination" late Wednesday, saying it would demonstrate the agency's commitment to cooperation with states.
"We believe we need to have a dialogue with our state partners and listen to them," EPA chief Scott Pruitt said in a statement.
Pruitt had announced in June the EPA's intention to postpone ozone determinations, which measure smog pollution in different parts of the country in order to determine where its level should be reduced by one year to meet the stricter air quality standard, to be reduced to one year into October 2018.
The 15 principally democratic states filed a lawsuit with the District of Columbia on Tuesday, saying the decision was illegal.
President Donald Trump's administration has tried to pull back a number of environmental regulations imposed by former President Barack Obama. Trump said it was part of a more comprehensive growth boost plan.
But these efforts have provoked reactions among Democrats and conservation groups concerned about the impact of increased pollutants on human health.
The EPA's website states that inhaling air containing ozone "can reduce lung performance and increase the risk of respiratory diseases" such as asthma.
