From which corners of the world are they moving to Estonia?
Last year, the Police and Border Guard Board (PBGB) extended and issued a record number of more than 13 000 residence permits to third-country nationals who have mostly traveled to Estonia to work, study or stay with their families.
For example, last year it was decided to issue a temporary residence permit to 6702 foreigners, but last year the number was 4928.
The authorities cannot say how many immigrants will eventually remain in Estonia, but such an analysis will be prepared in the Ministry of the Interior.
While ten years ago nearly 500 Ukrainians moved to Estonia every year, in recent years this number is beginning to come close to 2000.
The number of applicants for a residence permit increased exponentially during the crisis in Ukraine - in 2014 1087 people received a temporary residence permit, compared to 675 the year before.
According to Statistics Estonia, the number of Ukrainian citizens is increasing the most in Estonia - last year, 850 more Ukrainian citizens arrived in Estonia than left.
"The Ukrainian community has always been large in Estonia, and due to difficult circumstances in the country, it is natural that work and study opportunities are sought in a country where the community and, for many, the family is already in front of them," said Kristin Rammus, spokesperson for the Ministry of the Interior.
Last year and last year, the number of Ukrainians who received a temporary residence permit was higher than even the number of Russian citizens, although in total, the largest number of fixed-term residence permits have been issued to the latter in ten years.
While Ukrainians come here mostly to work, Russian citizens come to work for family migration.
"Taking into account the historical Russian community here, they are also likely to have the largest family ties with people living in Russia," said Helina Maasing, migration researcher at the Estonian Academy of Security Sciences.
"If you look at where Russian citizens who have been granted an Estonian residence permit have moved to, there is immediately Ida-Viru County after Harju County," he added, pointing out that about 40 percent of them have married a European Union citizen.
Last year, 1696 Russian citizens received a temporary residence permit, which is also a record number.
At the same time, the number of Russians who wished to extend their residence permit decreased.
"The jump is due to the fact that a new residence permit has been applied for permanently to settle in Estonia instead of extending the residence permit," explained Rammus, a spokesman for the Ministry of the Interior, who said that the interest of Russian citizens in the Estonian residence permit has remained rather stable for years.
Foreigners who have resided here for at least three years can apply for a new residence permit for settling permanently in Estonia from the previous year.
Its purpose is to encourage the survival of adapted people.
However, a residence permit for a long-term resident requires, for example, five years.
The extension of the old residence permit has probably also decreased due to the new residence permit.
For example, last year, 146 Ukrainians who have worked here for at least three years were granted such a residence permit.
Now Ukrainians can change their jobs, and the Estonian state is no longer following whether the wage criterion is met.
This residence permit became popular last year - the applicants were still holders of gray passports (1029), Russians (487), Indians (54) and Nigerians (36).
A total of 1968 people received a residence permit for the purpose of settling in Estonia, including 23 Americans, 12 Egyptians, 18 Georgians and the same number of Chinese.
In the first half of this year, the total number of such applicants is already 1269.
In ten years, Nigeria has become a country whose citizens are among the most active applicants for Estonian residence permits.
While three residence permits were issued to Nigerians in 2007, 200 were issued last year.
They come to Nigeria to study at the universities.
Estonian higher education institutions are also popular with Georgians, Chinese and Turks.
The number of citizens of India, Bangladesh and Nigeria has increased largely due to study migration.
In their case, too, there is a rule that where the community has emerged in advance, it will be easier to add others," Rammus added.
