New results of Swedish asylum-seeker age assessment tests published
In Sweden, an accruing applicants tested a medically as their age with a novel approach. The latest results of the test show that more than 80 percent of the test subjects were rated older than 18, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of the results.
The Swedish National Institute of Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicineverket) started the tests towards the beginning of this year.
The tests were created to assess age more accurately during the course of the asylum application after the Swedish Migration Service (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to correctly determine the age of several allegedly underage refugees.
To date, the Migrationsverket has sent 6880 cases for testing, and the Institute of Forensic Medicine has released a total of 2481 test results between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) was rated 18 or older, and in another 25 cases, the Forensic Institute estimated that the "may be 18 years old or older" to be tested.
In 432 cases, it was concluded that a person is "presumably younger than 18".
The tests are only used if the person's age is in question.
According to Johan Göransson, who works at the Institute of Forensic Medicine, the results are consistent compared to those of previous months.
"We don't see much difference from the statistics of previous months, the numbers are quite consistent," he told The Local newspaper.
The fact that a large proportion of cases were rated older than 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers have been lying about their age.
The institute issued 581 test results in May and said that in 442 cases "there are indications that the person under investigation is 18 years of age or older."
But when the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the results of these 581 tests, it turned out that in 243 cases, the person had directly claimed that he would get 18 this year.
This medical method of assessing age, in the course of which X-rays of wisdom teeth are taken, and MRI of the knee joints, after which they are allowed to be analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has been criticized in some circles.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose duties include assessing the biological maturity of people to find out whether they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
"I have had reason to think about it and I do not think that the measurement method currently used should be used.
Determining biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can," he told Metro.
But Johan Göransson of the Institute of Forensic Medicine defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, it can be said that the risk of an inaccurate child being classified as an adult is low.
At about 10%, the risk is if the person is a little under 18."
