PSG will undoubtedly be able to spend such money to recruit Neymar and add it to its star-state lineup, considering that the team is funded by the family of Qatar's energy rich.
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot to recruit players, but they need to balance it with legal sources of income that allow them to get out with their own in the football business.
The FFP was founded by Michel Platini after he was elected president of UEFA in 2007.
This former French player believed that clubs that fall into big debt in search of success actually deal with cheating and risk ruin if banks or owners should drop the support.
Since 2011, the FFP has been focusing on tracking their losses instead of the debts of FFP clubs.
This change means that the business model that Roman Abramovich first used in 2003 in Chelsea - to buy a club with potential and then make large expenses to improve the team and create a global brand - is more difficult to implement.
During the current three-year evaluation period of the FFP, which will last until 2018, clubs can suffer losses of up to 30 million euros.
And despite Platini being disgraced from the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor, Alexander Ceferin, is committed to preventing excessive spending.
"The FFP is certainly not dead, and we will undoubtedly continue to strengthen these rules in the future," Andrea Traverso, who is a supervisor of the FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid for the Neymar overbought clause as a single payout, they will be able to split this amount for accounting purposes throughout the term of the contract.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, which is why it is possible to show the transfer fee as an amount of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
On the occasion of the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, PSG, along with Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City, were punished by the worst sentences.
PSG was fined 60 million euros (at the time 82 million dollars), which was later reduced to 20 million euros, and the club was required to limit the Champions League team to 21 players instead of the usual 25 in the 2014-2015 season.
UEFA is looking for clubs that may try to outsmart the over-regular financial institutions by blowing up their income through companies affiliated with club owners.
The Qatari company may sponsor PSG, but if the value of sponsorship is considered to exceed the standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to be accounted for as an official income.
This was the case in 2014 when UEFA decided that the value of the support from the Qatar Tourism Authority PSG was blown up.
It has been said that a certain part of Neymar's PSG service may come from Qatar through payments from the 2022 World Cup organizing committee.
However, PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar could become an ambassador for the World Cup, and argue that UEFA regulators could easily reveal such a manoeuvre.
The penalties imposed on PSG earlier mean that UEFA is even more vigilant in relation to any attempt to ignore the rules.
People familiar with the situation said Thursday that UEFA had not proactively discussed the transition of Neymar with PSG.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition that their anonymity is guaranteed because they are not allowed to discuss the PSG situation.
The latest published reports show that PSG earned more than 10 million euros in profit in the 2015-2016 season at a turnover of around 542.4 million euros.
