The NHS is about to prescribe HIV drugs that have caused conflict to 10 000 people
Since September, patients have access to "transformative" HIV prevention after a battle in the Supreme Court over whether the NHS should finance the drug.
NHS England announced that public health care is now making available to an estimated 10,000 people during the initial three-year clinical trial for pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) - a tablet administered before intercourse and has shown a reduction in the risk of infection by approximately 86% in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund a clinical trial after the Court of Appeal backed the Supreme Court's last year's ruling that the NHS would be able to pay for PrEP, despite the agency's own claims that local authorities should be financing the drug.
NHS England CEO Simon Stevens welcomed this move unveiled Thursday as a "new massive intervention" while the National AIDS Fund (NAT) described it as a "reverse moment."
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are among the first to register people. In October, there will be more clinics before the program is being implemented everywhere in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV drugs that are taken before intercourse to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
The results of clinical trials show that PrEP significantly reduces the transmission of HIV among people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that there are a sufficient amount of certain drugs in the human body that prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or at the latest two hours before intercourse.
Candidates eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are infected with HIV and are not receiving treatment.
Clinics identify suitable people who are willing to participate in the clinical trial, including men, women, transgender people and those whose HIV partner is not receiving antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and have chosen a family doctor there can also register their wish to participate in the local sexual health clinic participating in the program.
The program will cost 10 million pounds, and NHS England signed the contract to get the drugs this week after an international procurement procedure.
The purpose of the clinical trial is to assess the true potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence of who the drug is intended for and how it is widely consumed and applied.
Stevens said: "This new large-scale intervention should complement and amplify the widespread and increasingly successful fight against the spread of HIV.
This is another milestone in the fight against one of humanity's greatest health problems for more than three decades."
Deborah Gold, CEO of NAT, said: "This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if aimed correctly at those who need it and belong to a risk group, offers the opportunity to change the HIV epidemic in England.
Since September, people with high HIV risk in England, through this NHS-funded clinical trial, will have access to a powerful new tool that is individually manageable and independent of negotiations with a partner, thereby improving many lives.
We welcome this announcement warmly.”
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: "It is now essential to ensure that a clinical trial across the country is launched quickly and that no HIV risk group member is left out.
Now that the drug of the PrEP clinical trial has been obtained, we are on the road to protect more than 10 000 people who are at risk of contracting HIV.
Public Health Shadow Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: "The start of the PrEP clinical trial is very welcome and severely delayed after months of delays and dragging the government's legs.
Evidence shows how much change this medicine can bring about HIV prevention and the cessation of the spread of this life-changing infection.
This clinical trial brings us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that a clinical trial across the country is introduced as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to bring us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society."
