Eesti Pank bought 149 million euros worth of bonds in July under the public sector asset purchase programme of the central banks of the euro area, and the central bank's bond portfolio grew to a total of 4.36 billion euros.
The central bank does not disclose more detailed information about purchases.
In response to the interpellation of members of the Riigikogu, Hardo Hansson, President of Eesti Pank, has previously explained that the asset purchase programme of the Eurosystem central banks includes three different purchase programmes: covered bonds in the financial sector, asset-backed bonds (ABS) and public sector bonds (PSPP).
The central bank is buying bonds from the market to encourage investors who have sold bonds to invest elsewhere.
Purchases result in lower-risk asset yields and motivate investors to take greater risks.
As a rule, under the public sector bond purchase programme, each central bank buys government bonds of its own country, and bonds from other countries are not purchased.
As the Estonian state has not issued bonds, Eesti Pank makes so-called replacement purchases within the allocated volume.
Replacement purchases are also made by central banks in countries where the offer of bonds corresponding to the purchase programme is limited.
According to Hansson, Eesti Pank generally buys bonds from European institutions, such as the European Financial Stability Facility and the European Investment Bank bonds.
Eesti Pank will buy bonds under the asset purchase programme from March 2015.
In the meantime, Elering's bonds were also acquired, but Eesti Pank will no longer buy Elering bonds from June 2016.
From June, both Elering and Eesti Energia will buy bonds on behalf of the central banks of the euro area.
