Startups that help your business avoid becoming the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction in her e-commerce startup, but the surveys were revenueless.
The answers were often vague, useless or, even worse, misleading.
And even if he promised to ensure anonymity, some employees did not trust this process.
"This system was simply not consistent and objective," said Errett, who runs the 75-employed E-commerce company Madison Reed, which sells hair care products in San Francisco.
So he called outsiders to help.
New types of human resources startups are emerging to help companies figure out how their employees are feeling.
By developing and licensing software with a specific goal of measuring employee engagement, they allow companies to conduct sudden surveys, target specific teams and demographic groups, provide employees with an anonymity and a hot line for complaints, and in some cases allow language carriers to bypass C-level managers and contact the board directly.
"Now there are tools like Strava and Fitbit that are designed to monitor your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" asked Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Redwood City startup Glint, whose software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
According to Errett, he has gained much better insight into what his employees think and feel in the three years he has used Glint.
In addition to sudden surveys and surveys aimed at specific teams, it offers a company heat map that provides an overview of which departments have the most complaints and which managers have the lowest support, allowing them to find out the reasons.
Companies are beginning to realize that they need to stay up to date with their work culture in order not to become the next Uber that has been wrapped up in scandals since a former employee published a blog post describing a harassing environment punishing those who dared to speak out.
For startups like Glint, having an overview is a profitable business opportunity.
The global area of management, regulation and compliance may be worth more than US$111.7 billion by 2020, according to data from the financial technology statistics website Let's Talk Payments.
Convercent, a Colorado-based startup in Denver that helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, observed an increase in interest and activity in the background of Uber's dubious reputation this year.
The Convercent has almost 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Uber recently registered as a customer.
Like Glintki, Convercent lets companies send custom impulse surveys, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps from problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous messaging line that allows employees to report inappropriate behaviour.
And when it comes to the CEO, the complaints go directly to the board.
"Public opinion has been snatched by regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
Quinlan said that if a company is found to treat its employees badly or behaves unethically, the company could face serious consequences, such as consumer boycotts, employee departures and lawsuits, even if regulators do not intervene.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees in 500 sites, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure employees are aware of regulations and operations and provide an easy way to communicate with the corporate headquarters.
If an employee wanted to report a problem earlier, he had to find the phone number or email address of the headquarters of the corporation, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a daunting and uncomfortable process, said James Vitrano, a general adviser at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no good way to monitor employee complaints.
However, now that the company is using Convercent, problems such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair wage practices that did not previously reach executives who operated in offices in other cities or states can be identified and dealt with more quickly.
"I can get closer to the staff's holistic 360-degree experience," said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
"And we will protect our shareholders from litigation with employees."
Quinlan said the companies began taking ethical behavior, values and employee engagement much more seriously in 2002, after auditing firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations over the Enron scandal.
But it was only when "social media became mature" that companies realized that they could not prevent their dirty laundry from being washed online in public.
"Before using the technology to monitor ethical behavior, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a periodic fee for using their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity with the approval of venture capital investors who have been there to support both start-ups.
In February, Convercent was funded by companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, raising the value of the accumulated capital to US$47 million.
Glint was invested in November by Bessemer Venture Partners, increasing the company's total funding to 60 million dollars.
Such investments will come as no surprise when we take into account the interconnectedness of companies, culture and venture capital.
More and more research shows that modern workers expect more from the workplace than before.
In competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are merely tables.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued and that they devote their time to a company that has a positive mission.
"When people are happy in the company, feel that they are being listened to, and that the work they do is rewarding, they are more committed to ensuring the success of the company," said Nina McQueen, who is vice president of the general benefit and employee experience department on LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn income when companies in their portfolio are doing well; companies are doing well when employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee engagement and engagement, it’s no wonder they’re supporting.
Having data on employee involvement is important, according to experts in work culture.
However, this data is useless if the company's supervisors do not do anything with them.
In fact, when a company asks for feedback from its employees, it can create expectations that changes will lie ahead.
And if the changes do not happen quickly enough or not at all, this can lead to frustration and reduce employee engagement.
"If you ask for 4000 proposals, you have to be ready for 4000 conversations," said Russell Raath, president of Kotter International, a consulting and business management company, who has seen how companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
"Because if things don't get to the end, the employees will think, "Did you really listen to me?
- Do you care?
And if you don't care, why should I care?" "
According to Errett, Madison Reed, who is now conducting monthly surveys among the staff, has been able to implement measures on the same day that the problem has been reported through Glint.
And after receiving feedback from employees who were disappointed with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, he was able to reorganize several teams in the company and offer communication training to deal with the problems.
However, Ruby Tuesdays is collecting new data on employees and it is hoped that in the long term this will lead to a longer-term commitment of employees in an industry known for its high staff turnover.
"If you're not committed to ensuring transparency, you're losing people," Vitrano said.
"And if you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose businesses."
