The rules for handling genetically modified crops must be clear
The Ministry of Rural Affairs sent the Bill on Amendments to the Release into Environment of Genetically Modified Organisms Act (GMOVS) and the Plant Protection Act to the approval round.
The amendment to the Act will abandon the creation of a separate database for both genetically modified (GM) crop locations and handlers, for which the plant health register will be used in the future.
In addition, the obligation of the GM crop operator to have a prior agreement with a person engaged in beekeeping within the prescribed radius is amended.
Although genetically modified crops are currently not grown in Estonia, we consider it necessary to have clear rules for the coexistence of genetically modified and non-modified crops.
At least until it has been decided to declare Estonia GMO-free," said Sigmar Suu, head of the plant health department of the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
"At the same time, it must be taken into account that the measures developed must be purposeful and proportionate, taking into account the costs and administrative burdens related to both the private and public sectors," Suu added.
The Bill repeals the provisions of the GMOVS related to the database of GM crop locations and handlers and training on handling, and establishes the requirements for the handling of GM crops and the commencement of economic activities.
In the case of aerician, the current obligation of a GM crop grower to inform beekeepers of the initiation of cultivation of a GM crop is replaced by the obligation to reach an appropriate agreement with the beekeeper before starting cultivation.
The draft Act has been sent to ministries for approval.
All interested parties have the opportunity to examine it in the information system of drafts and, if they wish, to submit their opinion to the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
The planned changes will primarily affect persons, beekeepers and the Agricultural Board operating in the field of crop production.
In the European Union, including Estonia, it is allowed to grow only one GM crop - MON 810 maize.
So far, however, no Estonian farmer has been interested in growing a GM crop.
The reason for this is that there is no maize pest in Estonia, a European stemweed with a maize line MON 810 resistant.
Also, the varieties of this cornline are bred for the southern regions, and this corn is not suitable for our climatic conditions.
In order to obtain the above, the Ministry of Rural Affairs has commissioned studies in 2015 and 2016 to detect possible pollution with GM organisms in the seeds of various spring rape, corn and soy varieties grown in Estonia.
The results of the analysis of the samples showed that the seeds did not contain foreign genes and as a result of the study it was concluded that the seeds of rape, corn and soy varieties grown in Estonia do not contain genetically modified organisms.
In turn, it can be concluded that genetically modified crops are not deliberately grown in Estonia and it was also confirmed that there has been no accidental contamination.
