White House exhibit cost taxpayers thousands
According to military documents disclosed to TIME magazine, the White House's decision to launch a naval helicopter last month cost taxpayers as much as 24 000 dollars in the southern yard for an event celebrating American production.
The Green and White Sikorsky VH-3D, called the Marine One while the president was on board, was the central attraction of the event introducing American construction programs at the White House on July 17.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior officials from the White House explored industrial products from all 50 states on their tour.
The helicopter built in Connecticut was exhibited together with a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift made in Mississippi.
According to the records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the White House War Cabinet demanded a partial order with the helicopter's presence, or FARGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed in the southern courtyard for an "unusual" event.
"I wanted you to be aware of this because it's an unusually high-focused event," the HMX-1 commander told his boss, deputy chief of the Navy's officer in the field of aviation, the day before the event.
The message stated that the helicopter would arrive in the southern yard on the morning of July 17 at around 15 a.m. for an event starting at 5 p.m. and will remain there until the yard is cleared between 18 and 21 on the same evening.
The fact was added that if leaving the White House were to be delayed, a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to restrictions on working time.
The original flight crew was at the helicopter at the time of the event, and the security team of the squadron remained close to the aircraft throughout its stay on the ground.
It was not possible to read from the documents given to the magazine TIME whether the second crew was eventually needed or not.
The Hatch law prohibits federal workers from using government property for political purposes.
The documents show that HMX-1 examined whether this event could violate this setting.
"We asked if it violated Hatch's law, and we were told not to violate," the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to have a choice," replied the deputy of the chief officer.
The White House declared the event "American-made" official event, and Hatch's law would not have covered it.
But even at official events, there are political undertones.
The president supported the efforts of the health care reform that was discussed in the Senate at the time at the event and praised the efforts to keep the government's regulations under control.
Using an aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically profitable purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must use them to travel.
However, the requirement to use them purely for a photo session is unusual.
Trump came under scrutiny in February when his first campaign in Melbourne, Florida, was backing a presidential plane, and his Twitter account is full of messages complaining about how his predecessor used the president's plane.
"The White House is very pleased with the "American-made" display, where products from all 50 states manufactured by American workers from American materials were represented," said acting White House spokesman Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 teams often perform test flights around Washington and in the southern yard to practice putting down the U.S. president at the White House with an accuracy of a centimeter.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 held 58 trial landings in the White House yard.
According to the official, the flight to the "American-made" flight crew was included in the norm for the flight flight that month.
Squadron helicopters flew for an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidental support missions."
According to the White House, no other exhibit of this event burdened the taxpayer's wallet.
