The union expects the managers of the cookie producer McVitie to confirm the long-term production plans at the company's Glasgow plant.
According to GMB Scotland, the company has been silent about the future of the investment in the Tollcross object.
The factory, which produces Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies and other products, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie's, said they had invested more than 5 million pounds in the site over the past few years.
They hired more workers and trade union chairmen "are the first to hear" when something changes in the factory's activities.
In a letter to the company's site manager, GMB Scotland addressed McVitie's company with a request "to dissect concerns about the fact that the funding is not used to modernize production lines."
GMB senior organizer Drew Duffy said: "The fact that we are not clearing out from the head of the site about the business needs of Tollcross and the investment plan for the future is a matter of deep concern for our members.
