So Glasgow, in terms of jobs, wages and well-being in the eastern part of Glasgow, and against the background of Brexit, rising living costs and a chronic decline in production, urgently needs a company with a strong return at McVitie."
A spokesman for Pladis said: "The Tollcross site manager received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday, and the company will respond directly to him, as we value active communication with employees and trade union representatives.
Two months ago, a regular meeting was held in Tollcross between employees and GMB representatives, where a number of problems were discussed openly.
We then discussed with our employees that, like all other companies operating in an extremely competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are reviewing our activities on an ongoing basis - and this applies to all our companies and objects - in order to ensure our competitiveness.
He added: "In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in the Tollcross site, most of it has gone into production lines and operations improvement.
